<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by GRM Futures Group</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt 36pt; padding-bottom:4pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">GRM </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Futures Group </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Exec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">utive Summary</span></h1><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The submission will focus upon the following observations and recommendations:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GRM Background</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cultural Barriers to Partnership</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID-contractor relationship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – DFID staff appear more comfortable engaging with not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">profit organisations with some reluctance to embrace private sector companies.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Trends in DFID Expenditure</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Spending larger budgets effectively</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – Temptation to increase spending through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less efficient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> multilaterals and direct budgetary support, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less obvious</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> outcomes.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Implementation solutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– The benefits of experienced private sector contractors as an effective executive agency for DFID.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Value for Money</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– The importance in the procurement process, to focus value for money on outcomes and impact rather than inputs. Value from the private sector comes through efficient and effective delivery of aid with very small profit margins. Substantial reductions in fee rates affect the recruitment of the required expertise.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID Resource Restrictions</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Successful project implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– Best practice and innovativ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e developments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to be given due attention as quality indicators. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Flexible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">roject implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– The importance of flexibility of approach in fast changing environments to ensure the needs of beneficiaries remain paramount. The need for practical solutions to achieve goals rather than rigid frameworks.</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Spending through Contractors, Multi-laterals and NGOs</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Multilateral funding should be reviewed through a lens of results, impacts VfM and transparency. There is a need for open competition to increase the quality of development delivery.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The importance of NGOs in relief and emergency assistance is clear. However “not for profits” may offer less VfM than the private sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 101.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The importance of a balanced development delivery approach with attention to genuine value for money. </span></li></ul></ul><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">GRM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Background</span></h1><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GRM International, Futures Group and Effective Development Group comprise the GRM Futures Group of inte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rnational development companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with institutions, governments, and businesses worldwide to improve people’s lives.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We have managed more than 700 projects in more than 140 countries over more than 40 years for a broad spectrum of clients, including bilateral and multilateral funding agencies, governments, development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">banks, foundations, non-profit institutions, consulting firms and commercial corporations. With more than 110 current projects </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 85 countries, our group of companies has a global client base, multi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sectoral focus,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> diverse technical offering</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and a wide geographic reach. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">GRM Futures Group is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">K</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ey Supplier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to DFID with a firm commitment to the DFID ethos, including delivery of quality and value for money through all our projects. Our reason for contributing to the committee is to support transparent, honest, dialogue in driving best practice in the delivery of DFID development projects. The capacity and expertise of the private sector remains under-appreciated in UK development circles. This needs to change if DFID is to achieve its objective of developing increasingly effective aid delivery partnerships.</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cultural barriers to partnership</span></h1><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although recent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supplier outreach initiatives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">improve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d the situation, past relationships have been characterised by a somewhat suspicious attitude by some DFID staff towards private sector development contractors. Whilst the introduction of Key Supplier meetings is very welcome, relationships downstream also require a more collaborative involvement.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Relationship </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">between</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> DFID and Private Sector Development Consultancies.</span></h2><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important that the UK Government through DFID respects professional development contractors as important partners in delivering development outcomes, rather than seeing them primarily as profit seeking establishments. Many development management companies have developed their experience and expertise over decades, working for different donors in difficult and often hostile environments.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a perceived reluctance to embrace private sector companies into the overall DFID development fold as tried and trusted partners providing specialised technical skills and project management expertise at highly competitive rates, to the benefit of the UK tax payers and host country beneficiaries. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID staff can appear more comfortable engaging with NGOs and not-for-profit organisations; although our own Value for Money (VfM) evaluations suggests that private contractors are probably the most cost-effective deliverers of development outcomes. </span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rends in DF</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ID expenditure</span></h1><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Now that DFID has achieved the target of budgeting 0.7% of GNI for ODA, the debate is moving, rightly, from quantity to quality of support.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DFID’s ability to spend it’s increased budget efficiently and effectively.</span></h2><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The increase in ODA spending without a corresponding rise in DFID staffing, could result in increasing amounts of aid being channelled through multi-lateral agencies and direct budgetary support (DBS). We believe these delivery mechanisms lead to inefficient resource usage and sub-optimal development outcomes.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">olutions </span></h2><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Obtaining innovative and flexible delivery of a results-oriented portfolio depends on a fair process of open competition. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although only responsible for delivery of around six per-cent of the overall DFID budget, private sector development contractors are immensely experienced and qualified, and operate with no independent agenda of their own. They act solely as an executive agency, contracted to achieve DFID objectives on DFID’s behalf. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In many cases stakeholder organisations are more comfortable and responsive to working with private sector companies who demonstrate commercial acumen; understand problems and constraints; and are willing to explore innovative and pragmatic approaches to problem solving. </span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Value for Money in a competitive environment.</span></h2><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID has established effective private sector procurement processes, allowing highly qualified and experienced companies to bid competitively for implementing development projects. This approach encourages the submission of high quality technical, managerial and financial bids that focus on delivering the quality and functionality required, within the time promised and to the cost agreed. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is necessary however, to ensure that quality in terms of project management and project outcomes are not sacrificed to unthinking cost reduction, but that genuine value for money (high quality at a justified, reasonable cost) remains the procurement objective. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Fee rate comparison is possibly the worst indicator of VfM, focussing as it does on inputs rather than outputs, or better still, outcomes. We are keen to support DFID in developing more sophisticated methods of evaluating comparative VfM between bidders, moving away from equating negotiation of a discount with achieving value.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Profit margins in international development are extremely low. Increasingly, profit is only received once DFID has indicated its complete satisfaction of the delivery of outputs, while the risks passed to contractors by DFID continue to increase. An examination of the facts around project delivery cost suggest to us that it is hard to imagine anywhere else that tax-payers could receive better value, including through use of not-for-profit organisations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe we are among the most efficient deliverers of aid, ensuring that the highest possible percentage of spend finds its way to outcomes. We take significant risks and make available tens of millions of pounds working capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in doing so. In return, we are rewarded by perhaps 3 to 4 per cent in profit for a job well done. In the name of VfM, we urge DFID to fully examine the cost effectiveness of the various delivery channels available to it and, having done so, to increase the amount of spend through development management companies.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID fee rates can be less than half those of other UK Government Departments. They have been substantially reduced as a result of the quest to demonstrate value for money to the point where it is often now difficult to recruit the required expertise.</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">DFID Resource Restrictions</span></h1><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite staffing level restrictions, it is important that DFID remains fully engaged with implementing partners to ensure that projects are managed effectively and adapt to changing circumstances where necessary. The use of contractors provides cost effective, competent, flexible, management implementation, allowing DFID to focus on monitoring project impact.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Effective disbursement of the increased ODA budget requires larger projects effectively managed by competent organisations.  The Key Supplier Management process enables Key Suppliers to support DFID wherever possible, making specialist expertise and systems available as helpful.</span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Encouraging s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uccessful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">project i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mplementation</span></h2><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The essence of private contracting lies in the on-going development of best practice procedures that can be adapted from successful projects for use on others of a similar nature, leveraging previous investment in the same area. It is important that such innovative developments are given due attention in project proposal assessment and that these indicators of quality and enduring value, where contractors have an established record of exceeding project goals, be considered favourably. </span></li></ol><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Flexibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in project i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mplementation</span></h2><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When implementing complex projects in challenging environments, achieving the overall goals may require a modification of approach and flexibility by both the contractor and DFID to ensure that the needs of the beneficiaries remain paramount in project delivery. The political, economic and security situation in fragile states is relatively fluid and susceptible to change. It is necessary that project implementation adapts to this change and develops pragmatic solutions to continue the focus upon project goals without rigid adherence to logframe outputs which may no longer be valid or achievable.</span></li></ol><h1 style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:24pt 0pt 6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Spending through Contractors, Multilaterals and NGOs</span></h1><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Contributions to multilateral organisations such as the UN are required politically and this will obviously remain the case. The amounts concerned, however, should be reviewed in the context of results, impact, VfM and transparency. Many multilaterals do not demonstrate the adherence to fully auditable transparency, accountability and value that is demanded elsewhere by the UK government and seldom do they adhere to delivering outcomes to quality, cost and time. The goals and priorities of multi-laterals are also not always in alignment with those of DFID. We submit that open competition provides increased options and higher quality, better value proposals and implementation and that DFID should continue to push for these fundamental requirements from its multilateral partners.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">NGOs are also important partners in managing DFID bilateral spending, particularly in relief and emergency assistance where they have a great deal of experience. In terms of development delivery however, the advantage of NGO delivery mechanisms is less clear. NGOs have their own specific agendas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and modus operandi that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be incompatible with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID objectives.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is also a great mistake to assume that because NGOs are “not for profit” that they are in fact better value for money than private sector contractors; we submit that this is frequently (perhaps usually) not the case.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We believe that both multilateral and NGO partners are valuable and important in a balanced development delivery approach. However, given the demonstrable and auditable value for money and high professional standards available through use of private sector contractors by DFID, it seems axiomatic that increasing the relative percentage of ODA funds managed by them would contribute to enhanced value for money for the taxpayer, full transparency and accountability of funding and results, and increased efficiency and effectiveness of project outcomes for beneficiaries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We look forward to continuing to support DFID as a Key Supplier and genuine partner into the future and we hope DFID will increase its advocacy of the cost-effectiveness of our deployment and the innovative and impactful outcomes of our programmes.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p></div></body></html>